---
The Ninth Meridian catastrophe followed the failed rite meant to reconcile solar and underworld sovereignty doctrines across a single territorial claim.
The rite attempted to merge Solar Court and Moon Sovereign authority into a unified cosmic-legal jurisdiction over the corridor's central oasis belt.
It failed. The energy release propagated eastward along the Iseth Reach's dry channel, fusing surface sand into glass sheets across the Saltglass Reach's Glasswind Belt.
The thermal pulse was not uniform: near its origin point the glass is thick and opaque; toward the coast it thins into translucent sheets that shatter into cutting dust.
The older glass is milky (pre-catastrophe sand composition); newer glass is amber or violet-tinted (post-catastrophe mineral shifts), allowing experienced guides to read glass color as geological navigation.
The catastrophe's hydraulic effects were significant: it disrupted the Iseth Reach's remaining subsurface water movement and altered aquifer chemistry across the Saltglass Reach.
Kethari water-memory records these changes as a shift in the Reach's composition from pre-catastrophe baseline to post-catastrophe mineral saturation.
The Solar Court lost credibility as a universal governance authority following the catastrophe; the Moon Sovereign tradition lost several key institutional centers in the thermal zone.
The Jackal Synod emerged as a significant power partly by positioning itself as the party that had opposed the rite and whose funerary authority was validated by the mass death it caused.
The catastrophe's political aftermath reshaped territorial claims across the oasis-pyramid corridor and contributed to the Fracture Era's institutional fragmentation.
The Ninth Meridian's exact location is disputed: four candidate sites have been identified in current scholarship, none definitively confirmed.

