Kiess's founding narrative positions the Ninth Meridian catastrophe as the second in a sequence of institutional failures that culminated in Evermeet's collapse.
The catastrophe weakened the Solar Court's legitimacy; that weakening contributed to the instability that eventually destroyed Evermeet.
Kiess's three-power charter was designed to prevent both failure modes simultaneously: the catastrophe's problem (unregulated ritual authority) and Evermeet's problem (opaque institutional secrecy).
The anti-sealed-warrant doctrine applies directly to the Ninth Meridian: the rite was conducted without public documentation of its scope, failure conditions, or liability chain.
If the rite had been subject to Kiess's charter requirements — disclosure, three-power review, documented consequences — it would have been either modified to be safer or refused entirely.
Kiess's position: the Ninth Meridian catastrophe was preventable through institutional transparency and review requirements. Its lessons are prescriptive, not merely historical.
The Glasswind Belt's existence as a navigational feature is Kiess's most concrete evidence for this argument: the rite produced permanent terrain modification that affects route logistics to this day.
That terrain modification was not disclosed as a possible consequence of the rite. No one consented to it. Kiess considers this the foundational case for disclosure requirements on large-scale operations.

