Kethari water-memory preserves the most detailed pre-institutional record of the Ninth Meridian catastrophe's hydrological effects on the Saltglass Reach.
The catastrophe altered the Reach's subsurface aquifer chemistry in ways that Kethari water-readers track as a before-and-after comparison across their generational memory.
Pre-catastrophe water-memory describes a Reach with different mineral content, different aquifer-to-surface flow ratios, and different seasonal variation patterns.
Post-catastrophe water-memory shows the shift: increased silica saturation, altered salt concentration in the Mirror Flats' underlying deposits, and the unsounded depth zone where water-memory becomes unreliable.
Kethari analysis of the unsounded depth places its origin in the catastrophe's thermal pulse propagating through the subsurface along an ancient water-bearing stratum.
The thermal event partially fused the stratum, creating a zone where water-memory readings are contradictory because the aquifer itself was physically transformed.
Kethari water-readers have submitted this analysis to Mafdet's Quarantine Ledger and to Kiess's frontier cartography office as geological context for the unsounded depth's navigational designation.
Both submissions were accepted. The Kethari water-memory data is the oldest continuous record of the Reach's geological change and is treated as primary source material by both cities.
Kethari position: the Ninth Meridian catastrophe did not end when the thermal pulse stopped. It continues in the aquifer. The water still carries the wound.

